Does your state have the worst drivers?¶

Allen Ding

Introduction:¶

One thing that always seems to come to mind when I am driving around is the thought that "Wow, Maryland drivers are the worst!" Whether they are driving too slowly on the left lane, or merging without any indication, when I see that beautiful white license plate with the red and yellow trims this thought just keeps comming back. My friends from out of state also have shared similar sentiment but with drivers from their own state. This makes me wonder, which of the fifty states hosts the worst drivers? There has to be some way that I can prove to my friends that Maryland truely has some of the worst drivers out there.

Data Collection:¶

The data I am collecting comes from the Nation Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA). They use an annual census called the Fatality Analysis Reporting System (FARS) which is a nationwide census providing data to our government regarding fatal injuries suffered in motor vehicle traffic crashes. I am specifically looking at the 2019 report which has over 25 seperate csv which house all kinds of data regarding fatal traffic accidents including information about the people involved to information about the vehicles invloved and all the way to factors that may have contributed to the crash. The vehicle csv for 2019 alone has over 50000 rows with over 200 columns of different elements regarding each vehicle involved.

Source: https://www.nhtsa.gov/crash-data-systems/fatality-analysis-reporting-system

The first goal is to take the large amounts of data recorded and refine it into a smaller set of data that is less redudent and easier to analyze. There is a lot that can be left out such as the vehicle's VIN number and other identification that won't really help with our analysis.

I also needed to scrape data from the internet regarding information on the number of people driving in each state in 2019. To do this, I scraped a table containing highway statistics in 2019 from the Office of Highway Policy Information which is part of the Department of Transportation's Federal Highway Administration. This table contained specific data about the number of licensed drivers by state which I was able to scrap with Beautiful Soup. This information is necessary as it is used to normalize the data for the number of accidents for each state. I fitted the number of licensed drivers for each state into a dataframe and then used pandas to count the number of occurances of the state on the driver's license for each accident in 2019.

Source: https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/policyinformation/statistics/2019/dl201.cfm

In [3]:
# Requests information from the following url
r = requests.get('https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/policyinformation/statistics/2019/dl201.cfm')

# Scrapes the table from the webpage using Beautiful Soup and pops that data into a dataframe
soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text, 'html.parser')
soup.prettify()
table = soup.find('table')
soup_data = pd.read_html(str(table), flavor='bs4') 
df_driver_pop = pd.concat(soup_data)

# Drops unnecessary information so we can focus on the data from 2019
df_driver_pop = df_driver_pop.drop(columns=df_driver_pop.columns[1:71])

# Changes some of the state names to match the FARS data from the previous dataframe
df_driver_pop.at[1,'STATE'] = "Alaska"
df_driver_pop.at[8,'STATE'] = "District of Columbia"
df_driver_pop.at[11,'STATE'] = "Hawaii"

# Sets the state name as the index to more easily merge with out previous FARS dataframe
df_driver_pop = df_driver_pop.set_index('STATE')

# Uses pandas to count the number of occurances of each state on the driver's license for each accident that happened in 2019
num_accidents_state = pd.DataFrame(df['L_STATENAME'].value_counts())

# Joins the information counted above to our dataframe containing information on the number of drivers in each state in 2019
df_driver_pop = df_driver_pop.join(num_accidents_state)

# Cleans the dataframe up a bit by renaming the columns, dropping a redundant row, and converting insignificant floats to integers
df_driver_pop = df_driver_pop.rename(columns={'2019': 'num_drivers_2019', 'L_STATENAME': 'num_accidents_2019'})
df_driver_pop.drop("Total", axis=0, inplace=True)
df_driver_pop['num_accidents_2019'] = pd.to_numeric(df_driver_pop['num_accidents_2019'], downcast='integer')

Now that I have a dataframe with the number of accidents and number of licensed drivers in each state, I am able to display a barplot indicating the number of fata accidents per every 1000 people in each state in 2019. I used seaborn in order to get a nice gradient where the higher rate of accidents corresponds to a darker shade of red.

In [4]:
# Creates an array that holds the information of the normalized rate of accidents per every 1000 people for each state
arr = []
for _, row in df_driver_pop.iterrows():
    arr.append(row['num_accidents_2019']/row['num_drivers_2019']*1000)

# Creates a new column in our dataframe that holds this accident rate
df_driver_pop['Accidents_per_1000'] = arr
df_sorted = df_driver_pop.sort_values(by=['Accidents_per_1000'], ascending=False)

# Using Seaborn to create a barplot displaying the accident rate for each state
plt.figure(figsize=(16,9))
chart = sns.barplot(x=df_sorted.index.values, y=df_sorted['Accidents_per_1000'], palette='Reds_r')
chart.set_xticklabels(chart.get_xticklabels(), rotation=90)
chart.set_title("Fatal Accidents per 1000 people by state in 2019")
chart.set(xlabel="State", ylabel="Number of Accidents per 1000 people")

plt.show()

By looking at the data presented by the barplot, we clearly see that in 2019, Mississippi had the highest amount of fatal accidents per capita at over 0.42 accidents for every 1000 people while the District of Columbia had the least amount of fatal accidents per capita at less than 0.1 accidents for every 1000 people. However, is this conclusive? Can we end our search here and just say that Mississippi has the worst drivers? It might not be that simple of a question to answer after all. First of all, we need to take a look at our data and see how likely it is that it occurred under the null hypothesis. In this case, our null hypothesis is that there is no significant relationship between which state a driver is from and their likelyhood of getting into a fatal accident. Basically we want to test to see if our data is significant or if the variation is just due to random chance. To test this, I simply use the stats module from scipy to run a chi squared contigency test on the data gathered.

In [5]:
# Uses the chi2_contingency test from scipy.stat to get the p-value of our data set
stat, p, dof, expected = stats.chi2_contingency(df_sorted['Accidents_per_1000'])

print("p value: " + str(p))

p value: 1.0

Here we run the test and we get that the p-value of this data set is equal to 1. This means that there likely isn't any real significance between which state is on your driver's license and the likelyhood of getting into a fatal car accident. The variation seen in the data set can be simply explained by natural randomness and chance.

From looking at the barplot above of the rate of fatal accidents per captia per state, one thing becomes quite aparent. The bottom three states are Rhode Island, Massachusetts, and the District of Columbia. These three states are relatively smaller in landmass when compared to the other states and would likely correlate to a fewer amount of roads. If there are less roads in a state then perhaps, there is less likelyhood of accidents happening in that state. So now we have to collect some data on the amount of road lengths in each state to normalize our data once again.

Here we scrape information from the Federal Highway Administration once again to data on the total length of roads in each state. The whole data scraping process exactly the same as what we did before, we scrape the data using beautiful soup and put it into a dataframe. I then cleaned up the dataframe removing unneeded info and reorganized the dataframe to have the state as the index. This way when I try to join this dataframe with the road length info to the previous dataframe with our population and accident rate info, the two dataframes will already have the same index and will merge nicely. Additionally, I am dividing all of the total miles of roads values by 1000 in order to make the following graphs look neater as there will be a smaller range of miles.

In [6]:
# Requests information from the following url
r = requests.get('https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/policyinformation/statistics/2019/hm10.cfm')

# Scrapes the table from the webpage using Beautiful Soup and pops that data into a dataframe
soup = BeautifulSoup(r.text, 'html.parser')
soup.prettify()
table = soup.find('table')
soup_data = pd.read_html(str(table), flavor='bs4', header=0) 
df_road_length = pd.concat(soup_data)

# Shave off some of the unnecessary data
df_road_length = df_road_length.drop(columns=df_road_length.columns[1:14])
df_road_length = df_road_length.drop(index=[0,52,53,54])

# Reindexing the dataframe to make the merge easier
df_road_length = df_road_length.rename(columns={'TOTAL': 'Total_Miles_of_Roads'})
df_road_length = df_road_length.set_index('STATE')
df_road_length['Total_Miles_of_Roads'] = df_road_length['Total_Miles_of_Roads'].astype(int)

# Function to divide all of the total miles of roads values by 1000
def divide_1000(miles):
    return round(miles/1000,3)
df_road_length['Total_Miles_of_Roads'] = df_road_length['Total_Miles_of_Roads'].apply(divide_1000)

# Join the dataframe of road length onto our previous dataframe
df_driver_pop = df_driver_pop.join(df_road_length, on='STATE')

df_driver_pop.head()

Visualization:¶

So with our newly added road length data, I think an appropriate way to display all of the information is with a scatterplot. Using Seaborn, I am able to create this scatterplot with the total length of roads in miles as the x-axis and the fatal accident rate per 1000 people as the y-axis. Each point on the scatterplot will represent each state and with some seaborn magic these points are colored differently based on each state's rate of fatal accident per 1000 people. The size of each point is also representative of the population of each state. I think that these less relavent details are important firstly because they make the scatterplot more visual and exciting. But having the relative populations also displayed can help with one's understanding of the data. The population of a state in corespondance to total miles of roads helps to represent the relative density of each state. For example, New York and Oklahoma have nearly the same amount of roads yet Oklahoma has a much greater rate of fatal accident even though it has a much smaller population.

Now we need to see if the inclusion of the total length of roads matters in this context. We can solve for this by plotting the linear regression model between the rate of accident and length of roads for each state. To do this, I used Seaborn's regression plot to display the linear regression model fit of the data. If the line has a positive slope then we can say that there is a positive relationship between the rate of accident and the amount of roads.

In [8]:

scatter = sns.scatterplot(x=df_driver_pop['Total_Miles_of_Roads'], y=df_driver_pop['Accidents_per_1000'], hue=df_driver_pop['Accidents_per_1000'], size=df_driver_pop['num_drivers_2019'], sizes=(50,500), legend='brief')

# Using Scipy stats linear regression to get the slope and y-intercept of the model
slope, intercept, r_value, p_value, std_err = stats.linregress(df_driver_pop['Total_Miles_of_Roads'], df_driver_pop['Accidents_per_1000'])

# Plotting the linear regression line with Seaborn regression plot as well as labeling the equation for the graph
ax = sns.regplot(x="Total_Miles_of_Roads", y="Accidents_per_1000", data=df_driver_pop, color='r', scatter=False, label = "y={0:.5f}x+{1:.3f}".format(slope,intercept))

# Labels the scatterplot with x-axis and y-axis identifiers as well as a title
scatter.set_title("Accident rate per 1000 people by state vs Total miles of road in 2019")
scatter.set(xlabel="Total Length of Roads in Miles in Thousands", ylabel="Fatal Accident Rate per every 1000 people")

ax.legend()
plt.show()

print("Slope of the Linear Regression = " + str(round(slope, 8)))

Slope of the Linear Regression = 0.00046842

So interestly enough, the linear regression model has a positive slope indicating that there is some positive relationship between the number of miles of roads in a state and the fatal accident rate of that state. However, one should note that this only indicates that there is some correlation here which does not necessarily mean that there is some causation here. The number of miles of roads a state has is not the reason for the rate of fatal car accidents, there is simply a correlation here. A blog post that goes over this distinction quite well: https://codingwithmax.com/correlation-vs-causation-examples/

Further Analysis¶

So if the state listed on your driver's license doesn't meaningfully indicate if one has a higher likelyhood of being a safe driver or not then what does? The most common things I think about when I imagine a fatal car accident is that the driver was speeding, drunk, or distracted. I think it would also be interesting to see if people with previous accidents are more likely to be involved in another accident. The information is already in the FARS data so I just have to iterate through the data and extract the information thats there.

In [9]:
df_stats = df_driver_pop

# Get a list of the states that were used as the index
states = df_stats.index.to_list()

# Create 4 new columns to keep track of the number of accidents where each of these 4 categories were present
df_stats['Speeding'] = 0
df_stats['Drinking'] = 0
df_stats['Prev_Accident'] = 0
df_stats['Distracted'] = 0

# We iterate through each row in our orginal 50000 row dataframe and check if that row has any relavent information regarding if the driver was drinking, speeding, distracted, or had previous accidents. Once again, information regarding specific values can be found in the Fatality Analysis Reporting System (FARS) Analytical Users Manual, 1975-2019
for _, row in df.iterrows():
    if row['SPEEDRELNAME'] != 'No' or (row['PREV_SPD'] > 0 and row['PREV_SPD'] < 98):
        state = str(row['STATENAME'])
        if state in states:
            df_stats.loc[[state],['Speeding']] += 1
    
    if row['DR_DRINK'] == 1 or (row['PREV_DWI'] > 0 and row['PREV_SPD'] < 98):
        state = str(row['STATENAME'])
        if state in states:
            df_stats.loc[[state],['Drinking']] += 1

    if row['PREV_ACC'] > 0 and row['PREV_ACC'] < 98:
        state = str(row['STATENAME'])
        if state in states:
            df_stats.loc[[state],['Prev_Accident']] += 1

    if row['DR_SF1'] > 0 and row['DR_SF1'] < 99:
        state = str(row['STATENAME'])
        if state in states:
            df_stats.loc[[state],['Distracted']] += 1

Not so surprisingly enough, it turns out that a large amount of accidents involve either speeding or being distracted. The FARS data indicates that being distracted could be a range of things including being sleepy to texting to road rage. Though it does cover a lot of situations, all of them go to show that there are a lot of factors that could meaningfully contribute to the likelyhood of getting into a fatal accident.

To visually represent these 4 columns from the dataframe, I chose to display this with 4 different barplots that would join together as one large graph. There were several reasons for this. Firstly, the x-axis for all of these graphs would just be the list of states which they all share. Additionally, I am plotting the percentage of each factor present within all of the accidents for that state, so the y-axis for all of the graphs would also be the same. Lastly, it might not be the fanciest or more efficient way to do this, but I thought that this would have more clarity. I added the x-axis to the top of the graph as well to more easily use the subplots within the graph. The colors were also chosen to be distinct and each state throughout the 4 graphs would have a consistent color as it makes it easier to follow which state is which especially towards the middle.

One resource that I used to get these colors was: https://colorbrewer2.org/#type=sequential&scheme=YlGnBu&n=9 It allows for colorblind safe palettes and takes into account the nature of the data as well as the context.

Conclusion:¶

The state that appears on one's driver's license is not a good indication of one's likelyhood to be a safe driver. No matter where you are, there is bound to be a handful of bad or high risk drivers and for now at least this might not be avoidable. Although we found that some states had more risk of fatal car accidents, we calculated the p-value of that data to be 1 meaning that the variance in data is not significant and could be explained by chance. We tried to get a more accurate data set by also including the amount of roads in each state but that as well was not conclusive of any evidence that some states just have worse drivers. Finally, we looked at certain factors that could lead to fatal accidents and it further proves the point that it is not which state that matters but the behavior that people choose to abide by which has a greater indication of risk of car accidents.
